The site was designated as part of the "Sanzenzuka Kofun Cluster" municipal historic site in 1956, and the excavated haniwa were designated as municipal tangible cultural properties in 2004.

Isao Masuda hypothesized that the origin of the {{ill|Sakitama Kofun Cluster|ja|埼玉古墳群|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sakitama Kofun Cluster|qq=}} lies in the Hiki region and identified Raidenyama Kofun as the tomb of Halfebi, the grandfather of {{ill|Owari no Omi|ja|乎獲居臣|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Owari no Omi|qq=}}.<ref>Kuraji Nakamura, "The Musashi Provincial Family Conflict and Large-Scale Mounds," {{ill|Saitama Prefectural Museum of History and Folklore|ja|埼玉県立歴史と民俗の博物館|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saitama Prefectural Museum of History and Folklore|qq=}}.</ref>

== Excavated Artifacts ==
[[File:雷電山古墳 (東松山市) 出土 円筒埴輪.JPG|thumb|180px|right|{{center|Cylindrical haniwa}}{{small|Displayed at the {{ill|Saitama Prefectural Museum of History and Folklore|ja|埼玉県立歴史と民俗の博物館|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saitama Prefectural Museum of History and Folklore|qq=}}.}}]]
Artifacts include {{ill|morning glory-shaped haniwa|ja|朝顔形埴輪|1=Morning glory-shaped haniwa|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/morning glory-shaped haniwa|13=User:Immanuelle/Morning glory-shaped haniwa|qq=}}, cylindrical haniwa, and stand-shaped haniwa. These artifacts differ significantly from commonly known haniwa, as they lack brush marks typically found on their surfaces. This indicates a manufacturing technique closer to {{ill|haji ware|ja|土師器|1=Haji pottery|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/haji ware|13=User:Immanuelle/Haji pottery|qq=}}. Evidence of open firing, resulting in blackened surfaces, suggests that these haniwa were made in the early 5th century. These artifacts are currently on display at the {{ill|Saitama Prefectural Museum of History and Folklore|ja|埼玉県立歴史と民俗の博物館|qq=draft|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saitama Prefectural Museum of History and Folklore|qq=}}.

